  "prompt": "What is a masala bond?",
  "response": "A masala bond is a type of rupee-denominated bond issued outside India by Indian entities in overseas markets, typically priced in Indian rupees. Key characteristics include:\n\n1. Currency:\n- Denominated in Indian rupees\n- Allows foreign investors to invest in Indian debt markets\n- Helps reduce currency risk for Indian borrowers\n\n2. Purpose:\n- Raise foreign capital for infrastructure and development projects\n- Provide an alternative funding mechanism for Indian companies\n- Attract international investment in Indian markets\n\n3. Features:\n- Issued in foreign markets like London or Singapore\n- Primarily targeted at foreign institutional investors\n- Typically have fixed interest rates\n- Usually have medium to long-term maturity periods\n\n4. Benefits:\n- Reduces dependence on foreign currency borrowing\n- Helps manage exchange rate risks\n- Promotes internationalization of the Indian rupee\n- Provides diversification for international investors\n\n5. Origin:\n- The term \"masala\" means \"spice\" in Hindi\n- Introduced by the World Bank's International Finance Corporation (IFC) in 2014\n\nMasala bonds represent an innovative financial instrument designed to facilitate international investment in Indian economic development.",
